<Post title="Reward Shaping: Teaching an Agent What Winning Means" date="April 2026" activeTab="learned">
  <p>
    The first thing you learn building an RL system is that your reward function
    is everything. Get it wrong and the agent will find creative ways to maximize
    reward without doing what you actually want.
  </p>

  <h2>Version 1: Win/Loss Only</h2>
  <p>
    The simplest reward: +1 for winning, -1 for losing. The agent learned... nothing.
    With a sparse reward signal and dozens of actions per episode, the credit assignment
    problem was too hard. The agent couldn't figure out which of its 30+ actions in a
    fight actually mattered.
  </p>

  <h2>Adding HP Preservation</h2>
  <p>
    I added a per-step reward based on HP changes. Lose HP? Small negative reward.
    Block damage? No penalty. This gave the agent much denser signal and it started
    learning to play defensive cards.
  </p>
  <p>
    But then it learned to stall. If ending the turn meant the enemy attacks, the
    agent preferred to... just not end its turn. It would play every card it could,
    even useless ones, to delay the inevitable.
  </p>

  <h2>The Turn Penalty</h2>
  <p>
    Adding a small penalty for each turn incentivized the agent to finish fights
    quickly. Combined with the HP reward, it learned to balance aggression with
    defense — play damage cards when safe, block when the enemy is about to hit hard.
  </p>

